First, the postulated C 30 triterpenoid precursor (20
S
)-tirucallol could convert to (20
S
)-apotirucallol by undergoing oxidation and skeletal rearrangement. Subsequently, (20
S
)-apotirucallol may lose four terminal carbons of its side chain and undergo selective oxidation to generate C 26 quassinoid 1 with a 20
R
configuration. Furthermore, selective oxidation of the α- methyl group at C-4 could lead to the formation of primary alcohol 2 , which may be oxidized to yield a δ -keto-acid intermediate A . Decarboxylation of δ- keto-acid A could lead to the selective loss of the α- methyl group at C-4 and generate the C 25 quassinoids. The C 20 - and C 19 -quassinoids would be formed by cleavage of the C-13/C-17 bond, formation of the C 19 -compounds requiring the additional loss of carbon atom of C-16 ( Shargel et al., 2004 ). The C 18 skeleton differs from C 19 by loss of one carbon atom in ring A , probably due to a benzylic rearrangement resulting in ring contraction ( Finefield et al., 2012 ; Polonsky et al., 1985 ).

