Quassin (23) and neoquassin (24) ( Fig. 8 ) were the first two quassinoids isolated and elucidated from
Picrasma ailanthoids
( Murae et al., 1969 , Z et al., 1962, Z et al., 1961). Numerous species of the Simaroubaceae family have then been investigated and various quassinoids have been isolated and structure-elucidated. Class B 1 quassinoids possess two α , β -unsaturated carbonyl at C-1 and C-11 ( Barbetti et al., 1993 ; Charles et al., 1986 ; Daido et al., 1992 ; Fang et al., 2015 ; Kamiuchi et al., 1996 ; Koike et al., 1991d ; Koike et al., 1990a; Koike et al., 1990b; Krebs et al., 2001 ; Polonsky et al., 1979b ; Prema et al., 2020 ; Prema et al., 2019 ; Win et al., 2015 ; Win et al., 2016 ; Yang et al., 2004 ). Neoquassin (24) and javanicin B (31) are characterized by a hemiacetal group at C-16 (Koike et al., 1990b; Murae et al., 1969 ). 16- β -O-methylneoquassin (29), (16
R
)-methoxyjavanicin B (33), (16
S
)-methoxyjavanicin B (34), perforalactone C (42) and 4-keto-(16
S
)-methoxyjavanicin B (50) feature α - or β -OCH 3 group at C-16, while 16- β -O-ethylneoquassin (30) contains a β -OC 2 H 5 at C-16 ( Fang et al., 2015 ; Krebs et al., 2001 ; Prema et al., 2020 ; Prema et al., 2019 ). In addition, javanicin I (40), picrajavanicin G (41), picrajavanicin K (44), picrajavanicin L (45), picrajavanicin M (46), javanicinoside C (47) and 4-keto-(16
S
)-methoxyjavanicin B (50) are distinct with lost a methyl group at C-4 ( Fang et al., 2015 ; Koike et al., 1991d ; Prema et al., 2020 ; Win et al., 2015 ; Win et al., 2016 ).

