The C 
18
-quassinoids constitute a small group within the quassinoids, which originated from C 
19
-quassinoids by losing one carbon at C-2 (
Ang et al., 2000
). To the best of our knowledge, 473–479 (
Fig. 27
) are the only C 
18
-quassinoids isolated from nature (
Ang et al., 2002
; 
Ang et al., 2000
; 
Govindachari et al., 2001
; 
Wani et al., 1977
). A methoxycarbonyl group and a –OH group at C-1 are observed for compound 473, while quassinoids 474–479 exhibit an 
α
, 
β
-unsaturated carbonyl at C-1 (
Ang et al., 2000
). Moreover, eurycolactone B (474) feature a chlorine atoms at C-3 (
Ang et al., 2000
). In addition, eurycolactone C (479) was formed through a Baeyer-Villiger oxidation from laurycolactone B (475) (
Ang et al., 2000
).

After 2011, several researchers have studied the pharmacological mechanism of action. Eurycomanone (349) affects the expression of various cellular proteins which have multifunctional roles in cell proliferation and survival and are also associated with cancer development, progression and metastasis (
Wong et al., 2012
). The studies showed that eurycomanne induced apoptosis via p53 pathway by increasing the expression of pro-apoptotic Bax and decreasing anti-apoptotic Bcl-2 proteins; and the compound also targets other pathways affecting cell replication notably, including p53 tumor suppressor gene, the lung cancer cell markers hnRNP A2/B1, annexin I and probibitin. But its lipid solubility, oral bioavailability and the formation for effective delivery need improvement.

Zhao L J et al. investigated that the apoptotic induced by dehydrobruceine B (277) in human lung cancer A549 and NCI–H292 cells (
Zhao et al., 2016
). And the involvement of a mitochondria-mediate intrinsic pathway in the pro-apoptotic action of dehydrobruceine B was also reported (
Fig. 33
). The results showed that treatment with dehydrobruceine B decreased cell viability, induced apoptotic and blocked cell cycle at S phase. And they found that the dehydrobruceine B induced apoptosis is caused by mediating mitochondrial intrinsic pathway, which was evidenced by the loss of MMP, the release of cytochrome 
c
into cytosol, and the cleavage of caspase-9, -3 and poly (ADP-ribose) polymerase (PAPR) (
Zhao et al., 2016
).
